  <mj-body background-color="#f9f9f9">

    <mj-section>
      <mj-group>
        <mj-column>
          <mj-image align="left" src="https://userimg-assets.customeriomail.com/images/client-env-167726/1726674956909_typedb-logo_01J82XHWQY0FX4E6DZKXR4QB15.png" alt="TypeDB" href="https://typedb.com" border="none" width="140px" padding="0px"></mj-image>
        </mj-column>
        <mj-column>
          <mj-text align="right" font-size="11px" line-height="17px" padding="0">
            <a href="{% view_in_browser_url %}">View this email in your browser</a>
          </mj-text>
        </mj-column>
      </mj-group>
    </mj-section>

    <mj-section>
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text align="center" font-weight="300" padding="30px 0 10px 0" font-size="32px" line-height="40px">
          <h1>We have launched the alpha for TypeDB 3.0: re-built in Rust</h1>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <mj-section>
      <mj-column>
        <mj-image align="center" src="https://userimg-assets.customeriomail.com/images/client-env-168018/1726836706408_880fea017f7884299450209b077c9fce6021512d-1792x1024_01J87QT36FFZS0TG96M2Y3MW79.png"></mj-image>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <mj-section>
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text>
          <p>This first release represents an early alpha launch of our rebuild in Rust. This gives us a lot more speed, stability, and scalability. In practice, that means we‚Äôd love to see you sandbox it and give us feedback, but it is not ready yet to be used in a production environment. </p>

          <p>Over the coming weeks, we‚Äôre going to be regularly deploying new features to take it to parity with 2.x. That will then initiate the 3.0-beta phase, where we'll process your bug reports, stabilise and optimize performance, until the first full 3.0 release.</p>

          <p><em>I personally cannot articulate how much incredible work has gone in from our team, because I joined this week. Apparently, it‚Äôs a lot. They‚Äôre very pleased.</em></p>

          <p>We're incredibly excited with the direction TypeDB and TypeQL have taken in the last months, and hope you will be too. Some top highlights:</p>

          <ol>
            <li>‚ö°Ô∏è Multi-stage query pipelines. Expressive Functions in place of Rules. Constraints. Lists. Structs. Many additional data types. It's way too much to pack into an email, so the curious reader can see the finer details in <a href="https://typedb.com/blog/typedb-3-roadmap">The TypeDB 3.0 Roadmap</a>.</li>
            <li>üöÄ Server rewritten in Rust. Built for safety and performance, the Rust language shares many of TypeDB's core principles. It's gaining popularity along many fronts, seeing increasing adoption, for example, in the development of the Linux kernel. Expect new performance and scalability profiles.</li>
            <li>‚öôÔ∏è Driver API that gets rid of Sessions and simplifies all query methods down to a simple <code>transaction.query("...")</code> interface. No more Concept API.</li>
          </ol>

          <p>
            Adding a second reminder to consider TypeDB 3.0 Alpha to be a "prototype". Do <strong>not</strong> use it in production systems yet (please!). The storage layer is subject to change as we optimize and stabilize, so there won't be compatibility. Do experiment and try the new features. Get a feel for the new <a href="https://typedb.com/fundamentals/constraints-3-0">constraint language</a>.
            Try creating complex DB workflows with <a href="https://typedb.com/fundamentals/pipelines-3-0">pipelines</a>.
            And tell us what's missing (this email address is monitored).
          </p>

          <p>We'll be posting <strong>new Driver API snippets</strong> in our Discord <a href="https://typedb.com/discord">Chat Server</a>.</p>

          <p>We're sure you'll love the new language, server, and drivers as much as we do, and look forward to hearing from everyone in the community.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <mj-section css-class="td-actions">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-button href="https://github.com/typedb/typedb/releases/tag/3.0.0-alpha-1">Try TypeDB 3.0</mj-button>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <mj-section>
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text align="center" font-weight="300" padding="30px 0 10px 0" font-size="32px" line-height="40px">
          <h1>The AWS and Azure Marketplaces now offer TypeDB Cloud</h1>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <mj-section>
      <mj-column>
        <mj-image align="center" src="https://userimg-assets.customeriomail.com/images/client-env-168018/1726842412710_Screenshot%202024-09-20%20at%2015.26.30_01J87X87QQD52ZYY1SPWRZZ53J.png" href="https://cloud.typedb.com"></mj-image>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <mj-section padding-top="0">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text>
          <p>
            Last month, Google Cloud became the first major cloud provider to offer TypeDB Cloud through its marketplace. We're delighted to announce that Amazon AWS and Microsoft Azure now have their own TypeDB Cloud offerings as well!
          </p>
          <p>
            Connect your existing TypeDB Cloud organization to your desired marketplace by following these steps:
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li>Your organization administrator should open the&nbsp;<strong>Settings</strong> page for the organization.</li>
            <li>Select your provider from the&nbsp;<strong>Marketplace Integrations</strong> section. You'll be taken to your provider's marketplace page, allowing you to subscribe to TypeDB Cloud.</li>
            <li>You'll now be able to pay for TypeDB Cloud deployments with that provider through the linked billing account.</li>
          </ol>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <mj-section css-class="td-actions">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-button href="https://cloud.typedb.com">Open TypeDB Cloud</mj-button>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

